      <div class="article-body" data-i18n="article.pod.body">
        <p>Print on demand (POD) is one of the few online businesses where inventory risk is zero. AI removes the last bottleneck — design skill. This guide covers the full path: niche selection, AI-generated artwork, platform setup, and marketing.</p>

        <h2>Why POD Still Works in 2026</h2>
        <p>Amazon Merch on Demand, Redbubble, and Printful remain active. Google search volume for "custom t-shirt design" is steady at 100K+ queries/month. The opportunity is not the platform — it is the design speed. AI tools now let you generate 50 on-brand designs in an afternoon where a human designer would need a week.</p>

        <h2>Step 1: Pick a Narrow Niche</h2>
        <p>Avoid saturated niches like "funny cat t-shirts." Target micro-audiences with identifiable aesthetics: trail runners who like topographic maps, mechanical-keyboard builders who love 60% layouts, Rottweiler owners who read. Narrow niches have lower competition and higher willingness to pay.</p>

        <h2>Step 2: Generate Designs with AI</h2>
        <p>Midjourney, DALL-E 3, and Ideogram all produce usable POD artwork. For text-heavy designs, Ideogram is currently the most reliable at rendering legible typography. For retro/illustrated styles, Midjourney v6.1 still leads.</p>

        <h2>Step 3: Validate Before Uploading</h2>
        <p>Upload 5-10 designs to Redbubble or Etsy and measure views over 7 days. If average views per design is under 50, the niche is too cold or the artwork is too generic. Move on before ordering samples.</p>

        <h2>Realistic First-Month Income Estimate</h2>
        <p>Month 1: $50-$200. Month 6: $500-$2,000 with a catalog of 20-50 products. These are approximate outcomes; your niche and design quality will change the numbers.</p>

        <h2>Step 4: Automation Stack</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Design: Midjourney + Canva for text layout</li>
          <li>Keyword research: NeuronWriter for product titles and tags</li>
          <li>Publishing: Printful + Etsy/Amazon Merch</li>
          <li>Customer service: Gorgias or helpdesk automation</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Common Mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Uploading 200 designs at once without taste filtering — platforms flag spam</li>
          <li>Ignoring trademark — do not use NFL, Disney, or brand names in designs</li>
          <li>Relying on one platform only — diversify across Printful, Redbubble, and Amazon Merch</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Conclusion</h2>
        <p>POD with AI is a volume-and-taste game. Upload consistently, retire designs that do not sell after 30 days, and double down on niches where you have genuine interest. Interest shows in the art and buyers notice.</p>
